sql:
SELECT st.solve_type_name, s.solve_id
FROM solutions s
INNER JOIN solve_types st ON s.solve_type = st.solve_type_id;

SELECT solve_type, COUNT(solve_id) AS number_of_solutions
FROM solutions
GROUP BY solve_type;

SELECT COUNT(solve_id) AS total_completed_solutions
FROM solutions
WHERE status = 'completed';

SELECT solve_id, objective_value
FROM solutions
ORDER BY objective_value DESC;

SELECT AVG(total_cpu_time) AS average_cpu_time
FROM solutions
WHERE threshold_proportion > 0.5;

SELECT COUNT(*) AS problem_count
FROM problem_solves
WHERE user_id = 1;

SELECT solve_id
FROM solutions
WHERE total_cpu_time > (SELECT AVG(total_cpu_time) FROM solutions);

external_knowledge:
- 'Approaches' in this context refer to 'solve types'.;
- 'Best overall performance' means higher average performance. The higher the average performance, the better the approach.;
- The 'average of all metric values' refers to the calculated average performance values for each solve type. The performance is averaged across all the metrics measured for those solve types.;

- 'Exact' solve types refer to methods that find the precise solution to a problem;
- 'Simplex' method is a popular algorithm used in linear programming for solving optimization problems;
- A minute is considered as 60 units of time, so 'more than a minute' implies greater than 100 units in this context;
- The average CPU time is calculated for each category and only those exceeding 100 units are of interest.

